{{Japanese kana navigation}}

In this lesson you are going to learn how to read and write "ゐ" and "ゑ".  These characters are not used in modern Japanese but are found in old Japanese texts. They are included here mostly for completeness. The student can choose whether to memorise these. Most study aids will not practise these.

{{Japanese kana
| kana = ゐ
| sound = Exactly the same as <big style="font-size: 150%;">I</big>, but in ancient times there was a clear difference.  Scholars guess that the sound was something like <big style="font-size: 150%;">Wi</big>.
| example =
* ゐ (i) well (normally written in hiragana as い, but sometimes written in the former way to differentiate it)
}}
{{Japanese kana
| kana = ゑ
| sound = Exactly the same as <big style="font-size: 150%;">E</big>, but in ancient times there was a clear difference.  Scholars guess that the sound was something like <big style="font-size: 150%;">We</big>.
| example =
* ゑびす (ebisu) Ebisu, one of the seven lucky gods, and also the name of a Japanese beer.
}}

[[Category:Japanese|Hiragana 11]]

{{Template:Japanese kana navigation}}
In this lesson you are going to learn how to read and write ヰ and ヱ. These characters are not in modern Japanese but because they were legitimate characters before, one sees them in old Japanese text.

{{Japanese kana
 | kana     = ヰ
 | sound    = It is pronounced the same as "イ", but in ancient times there was a clear difference.  Scholars guess that the sound was something like "ウィ".
 | mnemonic =
 | example  = Not normally seen in modern Japanese. Occasionally, ウイスキー (whiskey) is written as ウヰスキー.
}}
{{Japanese kana
 | kana     = ヱ
 | sound    = It is pronounced the same as "エ", but in ancient times there was a clear difference. Scholars guess that the sound was something like "ウェ".
 | mnemonic =
 | example  = ヱビス - Ebisu, one of the seven lucky gods. 
}}

[[Category:Japanese|Katakana 11]]

[[Puzzles]] | [[Puzzles/Action sequences|Action sequences]] | [[Puzzles/Action sequences/Barrel of Ale|Barrel of Ale]] | Solution ----
There are 6 operations that can be done in any order to arrive at one pint. These are: Filling the 5 pint mug, filling the 3 pint mug, pouring the contents of the 5 pint mug into the 3 pint mug, pouring the contents of the 3 pint mug into the 5 pint mug, empyting the 3 pint mug (presumably by drinking it), and emptying the 5 pint mug. Using these operations, there are two ways to arrive at 1 pint.
{| border="1" cellpadding="2" ! !!5 Pint Mug !! 3 Pint Mug |- !1 ||5 ||0 |- !2 ||2 ||3 |- !3 ||2 ||0 |- !4 ||0 ||2 |- !5 ||5 ||2 |- !6 ||4 ||3 |- !7 ||4 ||3 |- !8 ||4 ||0 |- !9 ||1 ||3 |}
Or, much more quickly:
{| border="1" cellpadding="2" ! !!5 Pint Mug !! 3 Pint Mug |- !1 ||0 ||3 |- !2 ||3 ||0 |- !3 ||3 ||3 |- !4 ||5 ||1 |}
